programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/17/79: After falling behind 3-1 in the 1979 World Series, the Pirates rallied to come back and take home a championship. Willie Stargell goes 4-for-5 with a home run in Game 7 to lift the Pirates to a 4-1 win over the Orioles.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/21/80: Tug McGraw strikes out Willie Wilson on a 1-2 fastball in Game 6 sealing the Phillies' 4-1 win over the Royals, bringing home the franchise's first-ever World Series Championship.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/20/82: With the championship on the line, Bruce Sutter comes into the game in the 8th inning to blank the Brewers. The Cardinals captured their ninth World Series win in a dramatic Game 7 win at Busch Stadium.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/10/1982 - Cecil Cooper plates a pair of runs on a go-ahead single in the bottom 7th inning and the Brewers hold on to secure a 4-3 win over the Angels, punching their ticket to the 1982 World Series.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/14/84: Kirk Gibson clinched the Tigers' 1984 World Series win with a three-run homer off Goose Gossage. With the win, Sparky Anderson becomes the first manager ever to win a championship in both the American and National Leagues.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/14/85 - Heading into Game 5 of the 1985 NLCS, Ozzie Smith had just 13 career home runs and none of them were from the left side of the plate. That's why when he walked if off against the Dodgers with a homer to right field, the fans went crazy.
programme.sub-title: Ozzie Smith hits unlikely walk-off homer

programme.title: World's Greatest: Extreme Animals
programme.desc: Extreme Animals features environments hostile to humans, but havens to many animals. Witness gorgeous glow-worms, high flying condors, parched thorny devils, emperor penguins, and polar bears in this journey through life on the edge.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Land Adventures
programme.desc: Most land adventures come with some risk - a chance to confront our deepest fears, resist the pull of the ordinary, and soar into the wild unknown.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Capital Cities
programme.desc: With visionaries, politicians, and activists, these metropolises are defined as the official seats of government. Dublin, Washington, and Taipei share broad avenues, museums, and monuments, but are as varied as the countries they represent.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Mega Cities
programme.desc: Mega Cities provide a bustling home to populations of over 10 million. Travel from the high-density living of Shanghai and Bangkok to the sprawling cities of Delhi and Mexico City, each the backdrop for dynamic cultures.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Grassland Animals
programme.desc: Grasslands are the great stages of the natural world where large animals play out spectacular lives in clear view of people, including lions, leopards, elephants, rhinoceros, cheetahs, impalas, kangaroos, wallaby, potoroo, bison, and wolves.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Island Arks
programme.desc: Cut off from continents, remote islands have become floating arks, attracting migrating species and forging new ones. Take a privileged glimpse into the secret lives of the rare and exotic species that inhabit these lost worlds.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Sacred Sites
programme.desc: Ancient in architecture and detailed in design, these man-made masterpieces stand as testaments to the strength of human faith. These sites endure as a timeless reminder of resilience, respect, and the need to reflect.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Water Adventures
programme.desc: We are captivated by oceans, rivers, and lakes - the power, the flow, the reflective stillness. And as we seek to get closer, we immerse ourselves in an expanding range of aquatic experiences.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coasts
programme.desc: Along coasts, one element ends and another begins. No two days are ever the same on a coastline: the only thing that remains a constant is the timeless power of the sea.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Forest Animals
programme.desc: Forest Animals gets up close with bears, koalas, moose, wolves, weaver ants, and Tasmanian Devils. This episode roves dark forests floors and soars above vast canopies of green in America, China, Laos, and Australia.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coral Islands
programme.desc: The reef systems that gave rise to coral islands support the vast majority of marine species on our planet, but they are under threat. Explore the delicate balance between exploiting and preserving these extraordinary natural wonders.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Wetland Animals
programme.desc: Wetland Animals dives into the swamps, rivers, and flood plains of the Everglades, Botswana’s Okavango Delta, Kakadu National Park in Australia, and the Amazon to see deadly crocodiles, piranhas, hippopotamus, flamingo, manatee, and platypus.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Flights
programme.desc: Our experience of the world’s greatest marvels is literally and figuratively elevated when we explore them from the air. Whether you travel by air balloon, helicopter, light aircraft, a grand perspective is always guaranteed.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Bridges
programme.desc: A bridge is a structure that’s designed to transcend, but a great bridge can define the place where it stands. Symbols of human ingenuity, beauty, and grandeur, bridges connect us not only to each other but also to the past.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Global Cities
programme.desc: Travel to the centers of wealth, power, industry, and innovation. From London to Tokyo, Hong Kong to New York, these are the cities that never sleep. The influence held in these economic hubs unites the global community.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Drives
programme.desc: A journey by road expands our horizons, allowing us to explore the depth and breadth of whole countries and continents, stopping whenever and wherever we chose.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanic Islands
programme.desc: They've been worshiped and feared over the millennia. But in the wake of drama and destruction, the elements give rise to cultures and nations so beautiful that we've come to know them as the world's greatest volcanic islands.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Iconic Buildings
programme.desc: In construction, only a few buildings can be groundbreaking. Vastly different in shape, size, and function, these diverse buildings prove there is no recipe for greatness, just the fundamental ingredients of vision, bravery, and imagination.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: The second world war was conflict on an unprecedented scale. Its battles set new marks for the sheer size of forces deployed and for the power of their weapons. In this episode we study the first battle at sea, and the largest army to have ever marched.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: A war that reached every continent and touched every sort of terrain demanded every sort of strategy. In this episode we examine battles fought at sea, and in the jungle, in city streets, invasions from the air, and retreats from the land.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Battles are almost always about territory. Advancing the front line, seizing the port, the city, the oil field. The fate of nations in the war rose and fell on battles that took territory. Singapore, Monte Casino, Stalingrad...all about territory.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Every war seized new tactics; some inspired, some desperate, all attempting to influence the course of battles. Campaigns waged against non military targets to demoralize. Suicide missions launched when traditional weapons failed. Rules were rewritten.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: A world war is a patchwork of actions. Land. Sea. Air. Massive, or small scale. The stories of these actions, are just as varied. This episode describes battles of amphibious forces, climate, geography, and the problems of supply.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Through history, armies marched to face each other on favored ground and clashed to decide a campaign, a war, an empire. With the 20th century that changed. The battles of the WWII happened anywhere and everywhere, in every weather and climate.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Some words transcend their origins as humble place names. They are carved into history as turning points which influenced the course of WWII, the fate of nations, and the make-up of our world. El Alameine, Okinawa, and Pearl Harbor.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Aristocrat and the Balkan Communists
programme.desc: Fitzroy Maclean, an MP and WWII spy, supported Tito's Communist partisans in Yugoslavia against the Germans, forging a lasting friendship and honored at Tito's funeral post-war.
programme.sub-title: The Aristocrat and the Balkan Communists

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Agent Garbo
programme.desc: Juan Pujol, MI6's WWII agent "Garbo," created a fictitious spy network in Lisbon, deceiving the Germans with crucial disinformation and influencing their strategies. After the war, MI6 protected him, and he lived in Venezuela until his death in 1988.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Christine Granville
programme.desc: Christine Granville, aka Krystyna Skarbek, a brave SOE agent, secured the release of captured comrades from the Gestapo before Operation Dragoon, earning the George Medal.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The French Triple Agent
programme.desc: Operation Cockade, led by MI6's double agent Henri Dericourt in 1943, aimed to deceive Germans with sabotage. Despite efforts, Germans withdrew divisions unconvinced. Dericourt faced a post-war treason trial and died in a mysterious 1962 plane crash.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Spymistress and the French Fiasco
programme.desc: After WWII, SOE disbanded, leaving Vera Atkins to uncover fates of 118 agents, including 13 women. Many were betrayed and sent to camps; some were executed. Atkins' quest continued, marked by personal impact and delayed recognition.
programme.sub-title: The Spymistress and the French Fiasco

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The SAS Italian Job
programme.desc: In 1945, during the Italian Spring offensive, SOE agent Michael Lees and SAS officer Roy Farran led a raid on German HQs at Villa Rossi and Villa Calvi. Despite orders to cancel, Farran attacked with SAS men and partisans, killing many Germans.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Dutch Disaster
programme.desc: Operation North Pole was a WWII German deception using captured SOE agents to mislead Britain. 47 of 50 agents were captured. Despite warnings, SOE ignored signs of compromise to maintain support, leading to a major intelligence failure.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Scholar and the Fight for Greece
programme.desc: Monty Woodhouse, a professor and a legend for blowing up the Gorgopotamos Bridge in Greece in 1942. In the British counter attack against Rommell at Al Alamein in North Africa it was vital to disrupt German supply routes, Greece.
programme.sub-title: The Scholar and the Fight for Greece

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Banker, the Norwegians & the Bomb
programme.desc: Sir Charles attended Eton, and then joined the Coldstream Guards. He won the Military Cross on the Western Front and, having survived the war, returned to banking.
programme.sub-title: The Banker, the Norwegians & the Bomb

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Double Agent Tricycle
programme.desc: Dusan Popov was almost certainly James Bond. Ian Fleming knew all the stories about him. Popov managed to persuade both the Germans and MI6 to keep him in the style of a millionaire businessman while performing a series of missions against the Nazis.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928
programme.desc: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928: Hitler appears to be eliminated after his failed putsch in 1923. Discover how the Nazi movement used democracy's tolerance in Germany to come back.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Democracy without Democrats 1929-1933
programme.desc: Democracy Without Democrats 1929-1933: A protest turns into a racist and anti-Jewish movement during the 1920s and the NSDAP use emotions to gain the loyalty of the people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Racial State 1933-1934
programme.desc: The Racial State 1933-1934: President Hindenburg suspends freedom of speech and Hitler comes to power in 1933. The first concentration camps for political opponents are set up.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Hidden in Plain Sight 1935-1938
programme.desc: Hidden In Plain Sight 1935-1938: In 1934, Hitler's government is firmly in the saddle. Most Germans support Hitler's anti-Jewish policy and the regime's terror soon escalates.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Up in Flames 1936-1940
programme.desc: Up in Flames 1936-1940: At the end of 1939, the German Army invades Poland. Examine how Hitler succeeded in pushing through his rearmament and war plans relatively unhindered.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942
programme.desc: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942: In the shadow of the war, the Nazi regime gradually advances its "final solution to the Jewish problem", culminating in the Holocaust.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: X-Rated
programme.desc: Adolf Hitler had a depraved sex life that he tried to keep hidden from the German public. He was said to be a chronic masturbator, a voyeur and that he engaged in sado-masochistic sex with women.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Body Image
programme.desc: Hitler wanted the world to believe he possessed super-human qualities but in private he was a wreck. This episode reveals the archives that confirm Hitler’s genital deformity, the alarming truth about his heavy drug addiction and the Parkinson’s.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Family Matters
programme.desc: Adolf Hitler's father was a violent, abusive man. His mother doted on her young son. This episode delves deep into the psychology of Hitler as the narcissistic child who grew into a malignant psychopath full of rage and deep hatred.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Suicidal Maidens
programme.desc: Using extensive archival research, this program explores the squalid secrets he lied and killed to protect

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Genocide 1942-1944
programme.desc: Genocide 1942 - 1944: Along with Treblinka and Majdanek, Sobibor was one of the camps used in Operation Reinhard, in which the Nazis murdered almost two million people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Armageddon 1943-1945
programme.desc: Armageddon 1943-1945: The defeat at Stalingrad in 1943 was the turning point of the war and convinced the Nazi leadership to intensify their terror and propaganda campaigns.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: From The "Protection Squadron" To The SS State.
programme.desc: From the Protection Squadron to the SS State: Trace the rise to power of the SS as we examine several perpetrators. Who was recruited? And why was the SS attractive to men?
programme.sub-title: From The "Protection Squadron" To The SS State.

programme.title: Beyond The Myth: The SS Unveiled: Heinrich Himmler

programme.title: Catfish UK: Levi & Will

programme.title: Catfish UK: Leanne & Jamie

programme.title: 48 Hours
programme.desc: Elizabeth Welsh's husband, Patrick, left her and their two sons what appeared to be a suicide note and disappeared. After investigating the situation, Elizabeth discovered that Patrick is still alive, living in Texas.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Getting Away with Murder?
programme.desc: A report on families who have experienced the violent death of a loved one and believe they know the identity of the killer but lack evidence to back the charge.

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Mother Accused
programme.desc: This report investigates alleged incidents of Shaken Baby Syndrome, focusing on accusations involving Paulette and Kelly Welch, a Mormon couple living in Idaho Falls, Idaho, whose adopted son Stockton died on May 1, 1999 following a fall in their home.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder in Spokane
programme.desc: A report that focuses on the murders in Spokane, Washington over a period of a little more than two years (1997 - 1999) of at least a dozen women, mostly prostitutes.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder They Wrote: The End of the Dream
programme.desc: A report on the charismatic Scott Scurlock, known as “Hollywood” because of his flamboyant style and effective use of disguises in the commission of crimes, successfully eluded capture for four years while effortlessly robbing 18 banks.
programme.sub-title: Murder They Wrote: The End of the Dream

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Cop Behind Bars
programme.desc: Patrick Bradford, was convicted of stabbing his mistress to death. Determined to win his acquittal, Deborah Nolan, a close friend, and staunch supporter of Bradford’s, quit her teaching job and went to law school to take on his defense.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder in Las Vegas
programme.desc: Ron Rudin, a wealthy real-estate developer disappeared from his home in Las Vegas, Nev. Later, the charred remains of his decapitated body were found in the desert. After a lengthy investigation police were convinced that Rudin’s wife was involved.

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Family Torn Apart
programme.desc: The murdered body of Bob Dorotik, a engineer and father of three, was found by a mountain road near his home in the foothills of San Diego, Ca. Despite her denial of any involvement, Jane, Dorotik’s wife of 30 years, was arrested for the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Double Jeopardy
programme.desc: The investigation of the September 24, 1988 sexual torture-murder in Louisville, Kentucky, of Brenda Sue Schaefer.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Fatal Attraction
programme.desc: Thomas Capano, a successful Delaware lawyer lived a double life, a devoted family man while having affairs. When Anne Marie Fahey, one of these women, mysteriously disappeared police were at first stumped. Finally evidence led to Capano.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Bitter Pill
programme.desc: Stella Nickell of Auburn, Washington, was sentenced to 90 year in federal prison for poisoning her husband Bruce and Sue Snow, a Seattle bank manager with cyanide-laced Excedrin.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Mystery of Slide Mountain
programme.desc: A report that examines evidence and unanswered questions regarding a June 1, 1998 auto accident on Slide Mountain, near Reno, Nevada, that led to the death of Rinette Riella Bergna and left the driver, Rinette’s husband Peter with only minor injuries.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Colonel's Wife
programme.desc: Ret. Col. George Maracek, a 69-year-old former Green Beret who served in Korea and Vietnam, has been charged with the 1991 murder of his Thai wife Viparet. He maintains that he is innocent.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Reasonable Doubt
programme.desc: In September 1999, Brian Eftenoff of Phoenix, Az. Was convicted of murdering his wife, Judi. It was alleged that Eftenoff forced more than a gram of cocaine down his wife’s throat causing her to die of a cocaine-induced stroke.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Babysitter
programme.desc: Chris Routh, a responsible 14-year-old honor student loved children and earned money as a babysitter.. On July 25, 2001, Emily a child in his care suddenly stopped breathing. Was this a case of murder, an accident, or natural causes. Police investigate.

programme.title: 48 Hours: While Innocents Slept
programme.desc: A report based on the murder case involving the deaths of two infants which were originally attributed to SIDS (Sudden Infant Death Syndrome).

programme.title: 48 Hours: Millionaire Boys Club
programme.desc: 48 Hours is television's most popular true-crime series, investigating shocking cases and compelling real-life dramas with journalistic integrity and cutting-edge style.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Mystery in Room 813
programme.desc: On November 13, 1996, at a Sheraton hotel east of Los Angeles, 27-year-old Sandra Orellana of Houston, on a business trip with her 33-year-old boss Robert Salazar, went over a balcony and met her death.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Negotiators
programme.desc: An inside look at 23-year-old Jarrett Jordan, a disturbed man who shot three people and barricaded himself in a house in Queens, NY. He had with him his four-month-old daughter and three hostages.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Prisoners in Paradise

programme.title: Goddess Remembered
programme.desc: This poetic documentary is a salute to 35 000 years of "pre-history," to the values of ancestors only recently remembered, and to the goddess-worshipping religions of the ancient past.

programme.title: The Street
programme.desc: A poignant adaptation of Mordecai Richler's short story candidly depicts families' responses to aging members. Through watercolor and ink, the filmmaker captures raw family emotions, reflecting harsh realities.

programme.title: Strings
programme.desc: Strings: a haunting film of intimate strangers linked by shared spaces. Comfortable connections fracture when a problem arises. Created with glass painting and stop-motion, it's visually stunning.

programme.title: The Sweater
programme.desc: Roch Carrier narrates a childhood mishap in "The Hockey Sweater." In rural Quebec, boys idolize Maurice "Rocket" Richard. When the protagonist receives a Toronto Maple Leafs jersey instead of a Canadiens one, embarrassment ensues at the local rink.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Is It A Womans World
programme.desc: This film, made especially for television in 1956, embodies the conventional myth that women indirectly exercise power through their ability to manipulate men through sex and marriage.

programme.title: A Mother And Daughter On Abortion
programme.desc: The document of an intimate conversation between a mother and her adult daughter. They speak candidly about their personal experiences in trying to obtain an abortion, and how, in different decade, each got caught up in the system and its rules.

programme.title: Perfecting The Art Of Longing
programme.desc: Using footage from security cameras, video calls and home-video archives, this experimental short film leads us on a journey through memory, family and faith, exploring the nature of connection and distance.

programme.title: Sunrise Over Tiananmen Square
programme.desc: Shui-Bo Wang's animated documentary intertwines personal journey with history, exploring China's '60s-'80s upheavals. From symbol of hope to tragedy, it depicts Wang's roles from Red Guard to teacher, exploring idealism and intolerance.

programme.title: If You Love This Planet
programme.desc: This film records a lecture given to students by outspoken nuclear critic, Dr. Helen Caldicott, president of Physicians for Social Responsibility in the United States. Her message is clear: disarmament cannot be postponed.

programme.title: Chaque Enfant
programme.desc: This is the story of a baby who appears mysteriously on the doorstep of a busy executive, and who is subsequently bounced from household to household down the block. Nobody in the community is interested in caring for the baby without a name.

programme.title: Notmans World
programme.desc: William Notman was a man of rare talent. Photography was still in its infancy when he opened his first studio--in Montréal--in the late 1850s. He rapidly turned his art, and a budding technology, into a highly successful business.

programme.title: Mary Two-Axe Earley I Am Indian Again
programme.desc: This film shares the powerful story of Mary Two-Axe Earley, who fought for more than two decades to challenge sex discrimination against First Nations women embedded in Canada’s Indian Act and became a key figure in Canada’s women’s rights movement.

programme.title: The Secret Order
programme.desc: Phil Comeau shines a spotlight on the Ordre de Jacques-Cartier and paints a gripping portrait of the social and political struggles of Canadian francophone-minority communities.

programme.title: Canada Vignettes Log Drivers Waltz
programme.desc: A young girl who loves to dance and is ready to marry chooses a log driver over his more well-to-do, land-loving competition. Driving logs down the river has made him the best dancing partner to be found.

programme.title: The Man Who Stole Dreams
programme.desc: This enchanting and magical animation film, an ode to our dreams during the night, celebrates the creative imagination, uniqueness, and the human spirit. The plot involves a man who steals the dreams of villagers, the tries to sell them back to the them.

programme.title: Tu As Crie Let Me Go
programme.desc: In "Tu as crié LET ME GO," Anne Claire Poirier explores her daughter's tragic descent into drugs and prostitution, seeking understanding of the societal pressures influencing young people's risky behaviors in Montreal's streets.

programme.title: Best Time Of My Life Portraits Of Women In Mid-Life, The
programme.desc: An upbeat, positive film about a group of women dealing with mid-life and menopause. The women come from a wide range of backgrounds, careers and lifestyles, it effectively dispels popular myths and fears about life during and after menopause.

programme.title: Gurdeep Singh Bains
programme.desc: Gurdeep is a thirteen-year-old Canadian Sikh whose family runs a dairy farm near Chilliwack, British Columbia. They have retained their language and religion. Sometimes he feels a little different from the other children because he wears a turban.

programme.title: Le Grand Serpent Du Monde
programme.desc: A young forty-something, Tom Paradise refuses to grow up. Behind the wheel of his bus he drives endlessly through the city, tracing out the path of his life, dreaming of the landscape of the American West that forever impressed him

programme.title: Challenger An Industrial Romance
programme.desc: Follows the development of Canadair's super-executive jet. The film captures the spirit of the Canadian air transport industry and its attempt to compete with the American leaders in the industry.

programme.title: Waiting
programme.desc: The patient Dinkas of South Sudan endure famine amid civil strife. Aid arrives in Alek, but distribution is delayed to prevent unrest, revealing the stark reality of hunger.

programme.title: Benoit
programme.desc: Benoît is an astonishingly accomplished eleven-year-old Québécois from Joliette. He pursues such diverse activities as weight lifting and playing the violin.

programme.title: Very Nice Very Nice
programme.desc: Arthur Lipsett's debut film peels back life's facade, revealing hidden anxieties beneath. Through familiar images and fragmented speech, it critiques societal norms, punctuated by the recurring phrase, "Very nice, very nice.

programme.title: Ill Find A Way
programme.desc: When nine-year-old Nadia is allowed to attend a regular school, she knows the kids will tease her but she'll "find a way to deal with it." Nadia has spina bifida, a congenital condition that has caused a lack of sensation from the knees down.

programme.title: Mother Earth/La Terre Notre Mere
programme.desc: Mother Earth is a short, evocative, poetic film that celebrates life on our planet. This documentary film looks at the reality of human beings; the earth is our home and we are profoundly connected to all other beings.

programme.title: Sea Dream
programme.desc: Children, like adults, have days that go wrong. This film shows how one little girl overcomes the day's frustrations by diving into an underwater fantasy where she spends time with her friend, the lady octopus.

programme.title: Danish Poet, The
programme.desc: Can we trace the chain of events that leads to our own birth? Is our existence just coincidence? The Danish Poet considers these questions as we follow a poet whose creative well has run dry, on a holiday to Norway to meet a famous writer.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Wings On Her Shoulder
programme.desc: This is a 1943 recruitment film. Although it specifically promises women jobs in post-war aviation, its primary message is that women fulfill support positions "so that men might fly.

programme.title: King Of The Hill
programme.desc: Spring 1972. The Chicago Cubs are poised to win the National League's Pennant race, lead by their star pitcher, a Black Canadian named Ferguson Jenkins, who was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1991. This is his story.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Nigel Marvens wilde Philippinen
programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Ägypten
programme.desc: Ägypten bedeutet Pharaonen, Pyramiden und vor allem – Wüste. In der feindlichen Umgebung leben alle Arten von Tieren. Die alten Ägypter glaubten, dass diese Kreaturen die Natur, Mond, Tag und Nacht kontrollieren.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Das Meer verwandelt sich zusehends. Die azurblaue See von Durban unterscheidet sich grundlegend von der rauen Meeresküste des Kaps. Gemeinsam mit dem österreichischen Haiforscher Dietmar Posch startet Andreas auf eine Expedition in die warmen Gewässer vor der Küste

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Nigel Marvens wilde Philippinen
programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Das Perlenimperium von Palawan
programme.desc: Sie schimmert warm und golden, die Oberfläche ist makellos: So sieht die perfekte Perle der goldlippigen Auster Pinctada Maxima aus. Ihr Wert - mehrere Tausend Euro. In freier Natur findet nur sich in einer von 20.000 Austern eine solche Kostbarkeit. Das Unternehmen Jewelmer hat deshalb vor Jahren angefangen, in den Gewässern des philippinischen Archipels Palawan, diese Austern zu züchten. Bis heute beträgt ihre Ausbeute mehrere Millionen Euro pro Jahr. Diesen Erfolg hat das Unternehmen einer akribischen Forschung und einer rigiden Personalpolitik zu verdanken. Planet hat den Archipel besucht und beobachtet, wie lange es dauert, der Natur diese seltenen Kostbarkeiten abzuringen.

programme.title: Das Geheimnis der Schweizer Uhren
programme.desc: Die Wiege der Uhrmacherei steht in den Bergen der Französischen Schweiz. La-Chaux-de-Fonds und Le Locle - mit den Namen beider Städtchen verbinden Kenner höchste Präzision. Denn hier entstand im 18. Jahrhundert der Weltruhm der Schweizer Uhren - auf höchst ungewöhnliche Weise. Im Winter, wenn auf den Höfen wenig Arbeit anfiel, begannen einige der Bauern komplizierte Uhren herzustellen. Ein Handwerk, das über die Jahrhunderte in dieser Region perfektioniert wurde. Handverlesen sind heute die Studenten, denen hier der Sprung vom einfachen Uhrmacher zum Uhren-Restaurator gelingt. Jener Qualifikation, um die sich die Luxusuhren-Labels wie zum Beispiel Cartier, Zenith oder Ulysse Nardin reißen. Planet Weltweit hat einen Blick ins Innere der Luxusuhren und der berühmten Uhrmacherschule geworfen.

programme.title: Die letzten Kamelkarawanen der Sahara
programme.desc: Die letzten Kamelkarawanen der Sahara? Ein Film von Monika Hielscher & Matthias HeederBereits zu Zeiten der Pharaonen zogen sie durch die Sandwüste zwischen dem heutigen Sudan und Ägypten: Kamel-Karawanen, beladen mit Elfenbein, Salz, Straußenfedern und anderen Kostbarkeiten. Bis heute folgen die Beduinenstämme in der Sahara diesen uralten Handelsrouten, nur sind inzwischen die Kamele selbst die Ware, die nach Ägypten verkauft wird. Einer der wichtigsten und gleichzeitig gefährlichsten Pfade führt von Kordufan und Darfur nach Süd-Ägypten. Es ist der Darb al-Arbain - Der Weg der 40 Tage?. Nur erfahrene Karawanenführer trauen sich diesen Marsch zu. Planet Weltweit hat sich mit auf die strapaziöse Reise durch wüstenhafte Hitze und Trockenheit begeben.

programme.title: Die Holzfäller von British Columbia
programme.desc: Lange galt British Columbia als El Dorado der Holzfäller. Schneise um Schneise schlugen sie in den Urwald, holten die edlen Hölzer heraus, um damit die Bauwirtschaft oder die Papierindustrie zu beliefern. Die einseitige Ausrichtung der Wirtschaft auf die Ausbeutung der Wälder bereitet jedoch gewaltige Probleme, und das nicht erst seit der Wirtschaftskrise. Neue Lösungen müssen gefunden werden, um die Waldwirtschaft und die einmaligen Wälder zu erhalten. Auswirkungen hat dies auch für das Städtchen Revelstoke, in dem der Unternehmer Cal March sein kleines Unternehmen betreibt. Es ist eine der letzten verbliebenen Holzfirmen in der Gegend. Wir habenCal March besucht und mit ihm die Veränderungen erlebt, mit denen die moderne Holzwirtschaft die Zukunft meistern will.

programme.title: Die Meerfrauen von Japan
programme.desc: "Ama" nennen sie sich, Frauen des Meeres. Bis ins hohe Alter holen sie kostbare Meeresfrüchte vom Grund des Ozeans, trotzen der Tiefe nur mit der Kraft ihres Atems. Ihre Haut ist von Wind und Wasser gegerbt, ihre Stimme tief und laut. Seit Jahrzehnten teilen sich neun Frauen von der japanischen Halbinsel Shima ihr Schicksal auf einem Boot und sind dabei zu einer eigenen engen Meeres-Familie zusammengewachsen. Kazu Yamamoto ist mit ihren knapp 80 Jahren die Älteste der Gruppe, eine Ama in fünfter Generation. Ans Aufhören denkt sie längst noch nicht: "Im Meer kann ich meinen Körper besser fühlen und bewegen als an Land. Einmal im Wasser, verschwinden alle Schmerzen, auch der Rücken tut mir plötzlich nicht mehr weh", erzählt Kazu Yamamoto. Planet Weltweit taucht in die geschlossene Welt einer Gruppe von Ama ein.

programme.title: New York
programme.desc: New York - Sehnsuchtsort für Menschen aus der ganzen Welt. Wer es hier schafft, schafft es überall. Das dachte auch junge italienische Fleischersohn Tony Amato, als er in den 1940er Jahren hierher kam, um sich den Traum vom eigenen Opernhaus zu verwirklichen. Zusammen mit seiner Frau Sally kaufte er ein heruntergekommenes Haus in der Bowery Street, einer damals berüchtigten Straße in Lower Manhattan. Das Haus, drei Stockwerke hoch und drei Fenster breit, bekam eine Bühne, einen Orchestergraben, einen Kostümfundus, Werkstätten und Lagerräume für die Bühnendekorationen. Der Saal wirkt kaum größer als ein Wohnzimmer - seine 107 Plätze sind immer ausverkauft. Noch immer ist Tony Amato Dreh- und Angelpunkt dieser Miniaturoper - selbst nur knapp 1,50 groß, in Turnschuhen. Hosenträger halten den kleinen drahtigen Mann, so scheint es. Die Stimme ist fest, die Augen strahlen. Er dirigiert, singt, springt, lacht, schimpft. Maestro Tony Amato ist 88 Jahre alt. Er steckt mitten in den Proben zu Cos? fan tutte?, der letzten Produktion der Saison. Planet Weltweit wirft einen Blick hinter die Bühne des kleinsten Opernhauses der Welt mitten in New York.Feierabendverkehr in Manhattan. programme.title: Wo Japans grüner Tee wächst
programme.desc: Kyuchu - Wo Japans grüner Tee wächstEin Film von Ilka Franzmann Grüner Tee ist in Japan viel mehr als ein Getränk. Er ist der Schlüssel zur japanischen Kultur - Genuss, Philosophie und Lebenskunst in einem. Grünen Tee zu trinken, gilt in Japan als Kunst. Im Frühjahr wartet ganz Japan auf den First Flush - die erste Ernte des edlen Sencha-Tees von der Insel Kyushu. Hier liegt das größte Bioteeanbaugebiet des Landes. Planet Weltweit begleitet den Herstellungsprozess von Japans legendärem Grüntee, forscht nach dem Geheimnis seiner heilenden Kräfte und zeigt auch, wie tief das Getränk inzwischen Japans Gesellschaft durchdrungen hat.Der 60-jährige Kazuo Watanabe hat sein Leben dem grünen Tee gewidmet, wie sein Vater, sein Großvater, seine ganze Familie. Der Biofarmer ist Teebauer und hat seit Jahren einen großen Traum - er will den besten Tee Japans produzieren. Wie nah er seinem Ideal kommt, zeigt sich auch dieses Jahr erst wieder bei der Ernte. Zehn Tage dauert es vom Beginn des Pflückens bis zur trinkfertigen Teeportion. Der Farmer setzt auf behutsame Herstellungsmethoden ohne Pestizide. Seine Plantagen liegen inmitten der imposanten Vulkanlandschaft auf der Insel Kyushu. Der nährstoffreiche Boden, das saubere Quellwasser und das subtropische Klima schaffen ideale Voraussetzung ...

programme.title: Der Whisky-Mythos von Islay
programme.desc: Die schottische Insel Islay ist Heimat von acht traditionellen Whisky-Brennereien, die unter Kennern einen ausgezeichneten Ruf genießen. Das Wasser, der Torf und das Jod des Meeres sind die besonderen Elemente des Whiskys, der die Insel berühmt gemacht hat. Doch nicht nur das: Die Herstellung des berühmten Getränks sorgt für Arbeitsplätze auf Islay, ist Stolz und zugleich Lebensgrundlage ihrer charismatischen Bewohner. Planet Weltweit hat die Insel besucht und erlebt, wie das schottische Nationalgetränk Leben und Arbeit der Menschen auf Islay bestimmt.

programme.title: Marokkos weißes Gold
programme.desc: Die Arganie, ein dornenbewehrter Baum, wächst nur im Südwesten Marokkos. Seine Früchte liefern das begehrte Arganöl, welches von den Frauen der Region seit Jahrhunderten in mühevoller Handarbeit produziert wird. Inzwischen kommen auch Europäer auf den Geschmack dieser einzigartigen Kostbarkeit. Und nicht nur das: Neben seinen kulinarischen Qualitäten lässt sich das Öl ebenso gut als Kosmetikprodukt und Heilmittel vermarkten. Planet Weltweit hat den Frauen Marokkos bei der aufwändigen Ölherstellung über die Schulter geschaut und beobachtet, wie sie sie versuchen, ihr traditionelles Kleinod für den internationalen Wettbewerb vorzubereiten.Sechs Uhr morgens in einem kleinen Dorf im Südwesten Marokkos. Die Männer sind bereits zur Arbeit aufgebrochen. Auch Arbia el Kasri verlässt das Haus, um ihrem Beruf nachzugehen. Vor fünf Jahren noch war es für eine Frau unvorstellbar außerhalb des Hauses Arbeit zu finden. In dieser Region Marokkos verlassen die Bäuerinnen eigentlich nie ihre Douar, ihre kleinen Dörfer. Doch nun sind es einige Hunderte, die sich wie Arbia täglich in kleinen Kooperativen einfinden, welche die Frauen selbst gegründet haben. Hier produzieren sie Arganöl - eine Kunst, die Marokkanerinnen bereits seit Jahrhunderten beherrschen. Das Öl ist überaus nährstoffre ...

programme.title: Gilberto Gil
programme.desc: Brazilian artist Gilberto Gil returns to Jazz à Vienne in France with a new round of singing that is inspired by his latest album ‘Fé na Festa': a mixture of celebration, tradition and even some rock now and then. Gilberto Gil, worldwide known for as musician and the Brazilian minister of Culture, was one of the pioneers of the cultural movement ‘tropicalismo'. This movement, with a strong character of social protest, combines elements of traditional Brazilian culture with modern art forms. Gilberto Gil's new sound clearly has its roots in Brazilian culture, yet it is always inspired by jazz.

programme.title: Art Blakey
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: Curtis Stigers
programme.sub-title: Curtis Stigers - Fly Me To The Moon
programme.desc: The Danish Radio Big Band joins forces with American vocalist Curtis Stigers to celebrate Frank Sinatra's iconic concerts at The Sands Hotel in Las Vegas. Curtis Stigers and the big band present the most popular evergreens from the American songbook of the 1950s and 1960s, one of which is the classic that lend the concert its name: “Fly Me To The Moon”.

programme.title: Jazzmeia Horn
programme.desc: Vocalist Jazzmeia Horn's 2019 Malta Jazz Festival appearance was a celebration of jazz's future, infused with the soul of its past. Featuring Keith Brown (piano), Rashaan Carter (bass), Irwin Hall (flute and saxophone), and Anwar Marshall (drums), the young singer's performance was a reminder of jazz's enduring power to speak to the heart. Situated at the Valletta waterfront outside Our Lady of Liesse Church, Horn's concert was a truly spellbinding experience.

programme.title: Art Farmer, Jim Hall, Steve Swallow & Pete La Roca
programme.sub-title: The Art Farmer Quartet live In England
programme.desc: Art Farmer: Live in '64 highlights an amazing one-hour concert featuring the great flugelhornist in his prime. Farmer's band includes legendary guitarist Jim Hall (fresh from Sonny Rollins' band), drummer Pete LaRoca, and Steve Swallow on bass. The legendary ensemble plays both standards and originals with ease and finesse and highlights why Farmer was considered one of the most innovative horn players in all of jazz.

programme.title: Bill Evans
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: Dexter Gordon, George Gruntz, Guy Pedersen & Daniel Humair
programme.desc: Dexter Gordon: Live in '63 & '64 features three concerts filmed in Holland, Switzerland, and Belgium that highlight the bebop legend's classic style and silky tone. These shows feature legendary side musicians such as Art Taylor (drums) and Kenny Drew (piano), and jazz classics “Blues Walk”, “A Night In Tunisia”, “Body And Soul”, and others. One of the most influential saxophonists in jazz history, Dexter Gordon is captured in sharp form and style in this 70-minute tour de force.

programme.title: Chucho Valdis
programme.desc: Legendary Cuban pianist Chucho Valdés brought his band ‘Jazz Batá 2' to the Malta Jazz Festival on July 19, 2019. The air was thick with anticipation as Valdés took to the stage, revisiting the small-group concept of his mythical 1972 Cuban album ‘Jazz Batá'. The batá repertoire – the deep classical music of West Africa – permeates Valdés' piano solos throughout the concert. Valdés's band consists of Dreiser Durruthy (Batas and vocals), Yaroldy Abreu (percussions and vocals), Abraham Mansfarroll (percussion), Ramón Vazquez Martirena-Bajo (bass guitar). They delivered a performance that reverberated through the historic island.

programme.title: Mike Stern
programme.sub-title: Mike Stern & Didier Lockwood: Jazz à Vienne
programme.desc: Guitarist Mike Stern and violin player Didier Lockwood sharing a stage: that promises a good show! After playing for years with Blood, Sweat & Tears, Mike Stern landed a gig with drummer Billy Cobham and then broke through with Miles Davis' comeback band in the 1980s. Didier Lockwood played in jazz fusion band Magma during the 1970s and is known for his use of electric amplification and experimentation. Together they perform a unique duo concert at the beautiful antique theatre in Vienne, France.

programme.title: Milky Chance
programme.desc: The German duet is back and better than ever! Milky Chance is the success story of two school friends, Clemens Rehbein and Philipp Dausch. After a long break, 2017 marks the release of a second, long-waited, album "Blossom". And, for the public, finally the occasion to discover live these new compositions, mixing rock, folk and electro pop. With reggae vibrations that can rub shoulders with house elements, Milky Chance has one of the most singular sounds. With the presence of musicians on stage, and if we believe the listening of the new record, we can expect more electric concerts, more electronic and even more energetic than in the past!

programme.title: Progressive Rock
programme.desc: By the dawn of the seventies, progressive rock freed bands of the limitations of four-minute songs, allowing musicians to evolve a single track over a whole side of vinyl, draw on classical sources and create music in more complex, time signatures. Moog Synthesizers were portable and affordable, allowing bands to create orchestral effects. Such devices added a spectrum of new sounds and possibilities for musicians. This new world brought artists such as Rush, Yes & Atomic Rooster into the mainstream.

programme.title: Soft Rock
programme.desc: During the 1960s rock n roll splintered into a rainbow of genres – musicians were experimenting. Soft rock began as a blend of the progressive rock quest for musicianship and the songwriter's love of pop. It originated in the late 1960s in Southern California and the United Kingdom. The style relied on simple, melodic songs with big, lush productions. This new genre established bands such as Supertramp, ELO & Barclay James Harvest

programme.title: Andrea Bocelli

programme.title: Paul Simon
programme.desc: During the first leg of Paul Simon's triumphant, 2011 U.S. tour, he thrilled hometown fans with a special club performance at New York City's historic Webster Hall. The show presents this iconic artist working at the peak of his artistic and creative powers in an unusually intimate setting. The 20-song, 90-minute set list was drawn from his legendary career and includes several songs that haven't been performed live in many years. "Kodachrome," "Mother and Child Reunion," "Gone At Last" and "The Obvious Child" are just some of the highlights as well as songs from Simon's most recent album, 2011's So Beautiful or So What (Hear Music/Concord Music Group) including "Dazzling Blue," "Rewrite," "The Afterlife" and the album's propulsive title track.

programme.title: Adrien Perruchon, Symfonieorkest Vlaanderen & Josef Špaček
programme.sub-title: Works by Ravel, Lalo, Ginastera a. o.
programme.desc: French conductor Adrien Perruchon and the Flanders Symphony Orchestra take us on a musical journey to Argentine, Spain, and Mexico, in this March 1, 2017 concert performance at Concertgebouw Brugge in Belgium. The program opens with Édouard Lalo's Spanish Symphony for violin and orchestra, Op. 21, featuring Czech violinist Josef Špaček as the soloist. This is followed by Mathias Coppens' Music for Orchestra, Op. 12. The program continues with Alberto Ginastera's Dances from Estancia, Op. 8a, and Aaron Copland's El Salón México. Also on the program is Maurice Ravel's famous Boléro. The program comes to a close with Arturo Márquez's Danzón No. 2.

programme.title: Evgeny Kissin, Nikolai Demidenko, Warsaw Philharmonic Orchestra & Antoni Wit
programme.desc: Antoni Wit conducts the Warsaw Philharmonic Orchestra in performances of Chopin's Piano Concertos No. 1, Op. 11 and No. 2, Op. 21. Soloists are Nikolai Demidenko and Evgeny Kissin. After performing the first concerto, Demidenko encores with Chopin's Mazurka Op. 17/4. Kissin closes the concert with Chopin's Etude Op. 10/12 and the Waltz in E minor, Op. post. This concert was part of the celebration of Chopin's 200th anniversary in 2010. Chopin composed the second concerto one year before the Concerto No. 1 and completed both works at the age of 20, before leaving his home country Poland and moving to Paris.

programme.title: Les Dissonances & David Grimal
programme.sub-title: Brahms - Symphony No. 1 in C minor, Op. 68
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances present Johannes Brahms's Symphony No. 1 in C minor, Op. 68. Brahms realized he was expected to compose a symphony that would match the musical standards established by Ludwig van Beethoven. After working on it for at least fourteen years, he completed his Symphony No. 1 in 1876. Brahms's symphony was hailed as ‘Beethoven's Tenth': a worthy successor to Beethoven's Symphony No. 9. Brahms's work contains several references to Beethoven. For instance, the main theme of the fourth movement – first appearing in the strings – resembles the ‘Ode to Joy' in the finale of Beethoven's Symphony No. 9. This performance was recorded at Philharmonie de Paris, France, in 2014.

programme.title: Mikhail Pletnev, Russian National Orchestra & Lucas Debargue
programme.sub-title: Pletnev conducts Bizet & Ravel's Concerto No. 1
programme.desc: Mikhail Pletnev leads the Russian National Orchestra (RNO) in a performance of Maurice Ravel's Piano Concerto No. 1 with Lucas Debargue as the soloist. The concert opens with a selection of music by Georges Bizet based on Alphonse Daudet's play 'L'Arlésienne'. The music is compiled by Mikhail Pletnev. The first movement of Ravel's Piano Concerto No. 1 contains five distinctive themes, of which three are reminiscent of jazz. Debargue's performance of Ravel's concerto is followed by Gabriel Fauré's Barcarolle No. 4. The performance was recorded at Tchaikovsky Concert Hall in Moscow as part of the Ninth RNO Grand Festival.

programme.title: Philippe Jordan, Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris, Choeur de l'Opéra national de Paris & Ricarda Merbeth
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125
programme.desc: Swiss conductor Philippe Jordan and the Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris recorded all of Ludwig van Beethoven's symphonies in 2014-2015. In this program, maestro Jordan presents Beethoven's final symphony: Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125. He conducts the Orchestre and Choeurs de l'Opéra national de Paris and four vocal soloists Ricarda Merbeth (soprano), Daniela Sindram (mezzosoprano), Robert Dean Smith (tenor), and Günther Groissböck (bass). Beethoven composed his last Symphony when his hearing had all but gone, between 1822 and 1824. Symphony No. 9 is the longest and most ambitious of Beethoven's symphonies. Most striking is the piece's finale movement, which includes a choir and four vocal soloists singing a setting of Friedrich Schiller's poem ‘An die Freude' (Ode to Joy). This performance was recorded at Opéra Bastille in Paris, France, in 2015.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Nigel Marvens wilde Philippinen
programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Ägypten
programme.desc: Ägypten bedeutet Pharaonen, Pyramiden und vor allem – Wüste. In der feindlichen Umgebung leben alle Arten von Tieren. Die alten Ägypter glaubten, dass diese Kreaturen die Natur, Mond, Tag und Nacht kontrollieren.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Das Meer verwandelt sich zusehends. Die azurblaue See von Durban unterscheidet sich grundlegend von der rauen Meeresküste des Kaps. Gemeinsam mit dem österreichischen Haiforscher Dietmar Posch startet Andreas auf eine Expedition in die warmen Gewässer vor der Küste

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Kinderstube Wildnis Bei den Affen
programme.desc: Die Tonka-Makaken bevölkern die Tempel auf Sri Lanka. In einem der Clans erblickt das kleine Affen-Mädchen Gremlin das Licht der Welt. Von Geburt an muss es sich in dem lauten Gewusel aus Familienbanden und Fehden mit benachbarten Truppen behaupten. Das Gruppenleben ist von einer strengen Hierarchie bestimmt. Die Machtkämpfe zwischen und innerhalb der Familienverbände bergen ebenso viele Gefahren wie lauernde Greifvögel und die angrenzende Straße. Allzu oft geraten die noch wehrlosen Babys zwischen die Fronten. Bei Übergriffen durch Ranghöhere müssen Mütter oft zusehen, wie unsanft mit ihrem Nachwuchs umgegangen wird. Nur jedes dritte Makaken-Kind kann sich durchsetzen und überlebt seine ersten Monate. Der niedrige Rang der Mutter und obendrein ihre auffällige weiße Schwanzspitze sind nicht die besten Voraussetzungen für die kleine Gremlin. Doch das aufgeweckte Äffchen lernt schnell dazu und entpuppt sich als wahre Kämpfernatur.

programme.title: Das Perlenimperium von Palawan
programme.desc: Sie schimmert warm und golden, die Oberfläche ist makellos: So sieht die perfekte Perle der goldlippigen Auster Pinctada Maxima aus. Ihr Wert - mehrere Tausend Euro. In freier Natur findet nur sich in einer von 20.000 Austern eine solche Kostbarkeit. Das Unternehmen Jewelmer hat deshalb vor Jahren angefangen, in den Gewässern des philippinischen Archipels Palawan, diese Austern zu züchten. Bis heute beträgt ihre Ausbeute mehrere Millionen Euro pro Jahr. Diesen Erfolg hat das Unternehmen einer akribischen Forschung und einer rigiden Personalpolitik zu verdanken. Planet hat den Archipel besucht und beobachtet, wie lange es dauert, der Natur diese seltenen Kostbarkeiten abzuringen.

programme.title: Das Geheimnis der Schweizer Uhren
programme.desc: Die Wiege der Uhrmacherei steht in den Bergen der Französischen Schweiz. La-Chaux-de-Fonds und Le Locle - mit den Namen beider Städtchen verbinden Kenner höchste Präzision. Denn hier entstand im 18. Jahrhundert der Weltruhm der Schweizer Uhren - auf höchst ungewöhnliche Weise. Im Winter, wenn auf den Höfen wenig Arbeit anfiel, begannen einige der Bauern komplizierte Uhren herzustellen. Ein Handwerk, das über die Jahrhunderte in dieser Region perfektioniert wurde. Handverlesen sind heute die Studenten, denen hier der Sprung vom einfachen Uhrmacher zum Uhren-Restaurator gelingt. Jener Qualifikation, um die sich die Luxusuhren-Labels wie zum Beispiel Cartier, Zenith oder Ulysse Nardin reißen. Planet Weltweit hat einen Blick ins Innere der Luxusuhren und der berühmten Uhrmacherschule geworfen.

programme.title: Die letzten Kamelkarawanen der Sahara
programme.desc: Die letzten Kamelkarawanen der Sahara? Ein Film von Monika Hielscher & Matthias HeederBereits zu Zeiten der Pharaonen zogen sie durch die Sandwüste zwischen dem heutigen Sudan und Ägypten: Kamel-Karawanen, beladen mit Elfenbein, Salz, Straußenfedern und anderen Kostbarkeiten. Bis heute folgen die Beduinenstämme in der Sahara diesen uralten Handelsrouten, nur sind inzwischen die Kamele selbst die Ware, die nach Ägypten verkauft wird. Einer der wichtigsten und gleichzeitig gefährlichsten Pfade führt von Kordufan und Darfur nach Süd-Ägypten. Es ist der Darb al-Arbain - Der Weg der 40 Tage?. Nur erfahrene Karawanenführer trauen sich diesen Marsch zu. Planet Weltweit hat sich mit auf die strapaziöse Reise durch wüstenhafte Hitze und Trockenheit begeben.

programme.title: Die Holzfäller von British Columbia
programme.desc: Lange galt British Columbia als El Dorado der Holzfäller. Schneise um Schneise schlugen sie in den Urwald, holten die edlen Hölzer heraus, um damit die Bauwirtschaft oder die Papierindustrie zu beliefern. Die einseitige Ausrichtung der Wirtschaft auf die Ausbeutung der Wälder bereitet jedoch gewaltige Probleme, und das nicht erst seit der Wirtschaftskrise. Neue Lösungen müssen gefunden werden, um die Waldwirtschaft und die einmaligen Wälder zu erhalten. Auswirkungen hat dies auch für das Städtchen Revelstoke, in dem der Unternehmer Cal March sein kleines Unternehmen betreibt. Es ist eine der letzten verbliebenen Holzfirmen in der Gegend. Wir habenCal March besucht und mit ihm die Veränderungen erlebt, mit denen die moderne Holzwirtschaft die Zukunft meistern will.

programme.title: Die Meerfrauen von Japan
programme.desc: "Ama" nennen sie sich, Frauen des Meeres. Bis ins hohe Alter holen sie kostbare Meeresfrüchte vom Grund des Ozeans, trotzen der Tiefe nur mit der Kraft ihres Atems. Ihre Haut ist von Wind und Wasser gegerbt, ihre Stimme tief und laut. Seit Jahrzehnten teilen sich neun Frauen von der japanischen Halbinsel Shima ihr Schicksal auf einem Boot und sind dabei zu einer eigenen engen Meeres-Familie zusammengewachsen. Kazu Yamamoto ist mit ihren knapp 80 Jahren die Älteste der Gruppe, eine Ama in fünfter Generation. Ans Aufhören denkt sie längst noch nicht: "Im Meer kann ich meinen Körper besser fühlen und bewegen als an Land. Einmal im Wasser, verschwinden alle Schmerzen, auch der Rücken tut mir plötzlich nicht mehr weh", erzählt Kazu Yamamoto. Planet Weltweit taucht in die geschlossene Welt einer Gruppe von Ama ein.

programme.title: New York
programme.desc: New York - Sehnsuchtsort für Menschen aus der ganzen Welt. Wer es hier schafft, schafft es überall. Das dachte auch junge italienische Fleischersohn Tony Amato, als er in den 1940er Jahren hierher kam, um sich den Traum vom eigenen Opernhaus zu verwirklichen. Zusammen mit seiner Frau Sally kaufte er ein heruntergekommenes Haus in der Bowery Street, einer damals berüchtigten Straße in Lower Manhattan. Das Haus, drei Stockwerke hoch und drei Fenster breit, bekam eine Bühne, einen Orchestergraben, einen Kostümfundus, Werkstätten und Lagerräume für die Bühnendekorationen. Der Saal wirkt kaum größer als ein Wohnzimmer - seine 107 Plätze sind immer ausverkauft. Noch immer ist Tony Amato Dreh- und Angelpunkt dieser Miniaturoper - selbst nur knapp 1,50 groß, in Turnschuhen. Hosenträger halten den kleinen drahtigen Mann, so scheint es. Die Stimme ist fest, die Augen strahlen. Er dirigiert, singt, springt, lacht, schimpft. Maestro Tony Amato ist 88 Jahre alt. Er steckt mitten in den Proben zu Cos? fan tutte?, der letzten Produktion der Saison. Planet Weltweit wirft einen Blick hinter die Bühne des kleinsten Opernhauses der Welt mitten in New York.Feierabendverkehr in Manhattan. Am Steuer seines Wagens sitzt der Tenor Vincent Titone und singt sich warm. Er ist auf dem Weg in d ...

programme.title: Wo Japans grüner Tee wächst
programme.desc: Kyuchu - Wo Japans grüner Tee wächstEin Film von Ilka Franzmann Grüner Tee ist in Japan viel mehr als ein Getränk. Er ist der Schlüssel zur japanischen Kultur - Genuss, Philosophie und Lebenskunst in einem. Grünen Tee zu trinken, gilt in Japan als Kunst. Im Frühjahr wartet ganz Japan auf den First Flush - die erste Ernte des edlen Sencha-Tees von der Insel Kyushu. Hier liegt das größte Bioteeanbaugebiet des Landes. Planet Weltweit begleitet den Herstellungsprozess von Japans legendärem Grüntee, forscht nach dem Geheimnis seiner heilenden Kräfte und zeigt auch, wie tief das Getränk inzwischen Japans Gesellschaft durchdrungen hat.Der 60-jährige Kazuo Watanabe hat sein Leben dem grünen Tee gewidmet, wie sein Vater, sein Großvater, seine ganze Familie. Der Biofarmer ist Teebauer und hat seit Jahren einen großen Traum - er will den besten Tee Japans produzieren. Wie nah er seinem Ideal kommt, zeigt sich auch dieses Jahr erst wieder bei der Ernte. Zehn Tage dauert es vom Beginn des Pflückens bis zur trinkfertigen Teeportion. Der Farmer setzt auf behutsame Herstellungsmethoden ohne Pestizide. Seine Plantagen liegen inmitten der imposanten Vulkanlandschaft auf der Insel Kyushu. Der nährstoffreiche Boden, das saubere Quellwasser und das subtropische Klima schaffen ideale Voraussetzung ...

programme.title: Der Whisky-Mythos von Islay
programme.desc: Die schottische Insel Islay ist Heimat von acht traditionellen Whisky-Brennereien, die unter Kennern einen ausgezeichneten Ruf genießen. Das Wasser, der Torf und das Jod des Meeres sind die besonderen Elemente des Whiskys, der die Insel berühmt gemacht hat. Doch nicht nur das: Die Herstellung des berühmten Getränks sorgt für Arbeitsplätze auf Islay, ist Stolz und zugleich Lebensgrundlage ihrer charismatischen Bewohner. Planet Weltweit hat die Insel besucht und erlebt, wie das schottische Nationalgetränk Leben und Arbeit der Menschen auf Islay bestimmt.

programme.title: Marokkos weißes Gold
programme.desc: Die Arganie, ein dornenbewehrter Baum, wächst nur im Südwesten Marokkos. Seine Früchte liefern das begehrte Arganöl, welches von den Frauen der Region seit Jahrhunderten in mühevoller Handarbeit produziert wird. Inzwischen kommen auch Europäer auf den Geschmack dieser einzigartigen Kostbarkeit. Und nicht nur das: Neben seinen kulinarischen Qualitäten lässt sich das Öl ebenso gut als Kosmetikprodukt und Heilmittel vermarkten. Planet Weltweit hat den Frauen Marokkos bei der aufwändigen Ölherstellung über die Schulter geschaut und beobachtet, wie sie sie versuchen, ihr traditionelles Kleinod für den internationalen Wettbewerb vorzubereiten.Sechs Uhr morgens in einem kleinen Dorf im Südwesten Marokkos. Die Männer sind bereits zur Arbeit aufgebrochen. Auch Arbia el Kasri verlässt das Haus, um ihrem Beruf nachzugehen. Vor fünf Jahren noch war es für eine Frau unvorstellbar außerhalb des Hauses Arbeit zu finden. In dieser Region Marokkos verlassen die Bäuerinnen eigentlich nie ihre Douar, ihre kleinen Dörfer. Doch nun sind es einige Hunderte, die sich wie Arbia täglich in kleinen Kooperativen einfinden, welche die Frauen selbst gegründet haben. Hier produzieren sie Arganöl - eine Kunst, die Marokkanerinnen bereits seit Jahrhunderten beherrschen. Das Öl ist überaus nährstoffre ...

programme.desc: Las extraordinarias vidas de la actriz Meghan Markle y el príncipe Harry. Con los mismos intereses, el príncipe Harry y Meghan Markle parecen encajar a la perfección. Ambos se han enfrentado a una educación difícil y han triunfado. Ahora triunfan juntos. Este especial de una hora, que incluye una entrevista con el biógrafo Andrew Morton, investiga el trasfondo social que hace que este matrimonio aventurero parezca totalmente acorde con la moderna Familia Real británica. Explora las extraordinarias vidas de la actriz Meghan Markle, una poderosa defensora de los derechos de la mujer, y del Príncipe Harry, que ha roto con la camisa de fuerza real sin perder su dignidad real. Ochenta y dos años después de que un romance con una plebeya divorciada de Estados Unidos condujera a la abdicación de un Rey, este matrimonio real establece y confirma un revolucionario conjunto de valores británicos.

programme.title: La Historia de Isabel I

programme.title: Los Condes Beissel de Gymnich

Julia Melchior explora la vida en el castillo, donde la condesa Jeanette comparte la historia de los Beissel, sus retos y el éxito de sus eventos, que mantienen este patrimonio familiar.

programme.title: Gemas Reales: Un Legado Revelado
programme.desc: La historia de un conjunto de rubíes históricos, usado por la princesa heredera Mary de Dinamarca, creado para la coronación de Napoleón en 1804. Desde su primera portadora, Désirée, hasta Mary en 2004, estas joyas han pasado por dinastías reales. Como las joyas de la dinastía Romanov, tienen lazos con la historia, simbolizando el poder y la opulencia de tiempos pasados.

Concludiamo la puntata di oggi nel cuore dell'Africa, nell'unico luogo del pianeta dove vivono i gorilla di montagna, parenti stretti dell'uomo. programme.title: Miracles of Nature

Successivamente, scenderemo di qualche migliaio di metri utilizzando la strada della morte fino alla provincia di Los Yungas. E poi verso le rive del lago Titicaca, il lago navigabile più alto del mondo.

programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널무주 안성낙화놀이는 줄을 타고 떨어지는 불꽃들이 마치 꽃과 같다고 해서 붙여졌으며, 전북 무주군 안성면의 두문마을에서 마을의 서당 학동들이 뽕나무숯으로 낙화봉을 만들어 불을 붙이며 노는 전통적 불놀이 형태입니다. 낙화봉이 만들어지는 과정과 타닥타닥 불소리까지 ASMR로 함께해보세요. (무주 안성낙화놀이 / 전북무형문화재 제56호)

programme.title: 바람을 드립니다. 서천부채장
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널공작선은 일명 방구부채라고도 불리우는 원선으로 오연선, 연엽선, 좌초선, 태극선, 공작선 등이 있는데요. 이 중 공작선은 화려하면서도 품위가 있어 옛부터 귀한 공예품으로 사랑을 받아왔습니다. 부채의 재료인 대나무의 채취부터 재료의 손질과 완성까지, 서천부채장의 손길을 통해 시원한 바람이 만들어지는 과정을 따라가 봅시다. (이광구 / 충남무형문화재 서천부채장 보유자)

programme.title: [오늘도 평화로운 갯벌] 짱뚱어의 하루, 신안 갯벌
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널신안 갯벌은 2021년 유네스코 세계자연유산으로 등재된 '한국의 갯벌' 중 85%의 면적을 차지하는 가장 넓은 곳으로, 수많은 섬과 섬 사이에 형성되어 독특한 생태·환경적 가치를 가지고 있습니다. 세계유일의 다도해형 섬 갯벌의 전형을 보여주고 있는 신안 갯벌에 살고 있는 귀여운 짱뚱어의 하루를 감상해 보세요! ※ 전라남도 신안군 신안 갯벌 / 한국의 갯벌 (2021년 유네스코 세계자연유산)

programme.title: [마음이 차분해지는 정원] 담양 소쇄원

programme.title: Gilberto Gil
programme.desc: Brazilian artist Gilberto Gil returns to Jazz à Vienne in France with a new round of singing that is inspired by his latest album ‘Fé na Festa': a mixture of celebration, tradition and even some rock now and then. Gilberto Gil, worldwide known for as musician and the Brazilian minister of Culture, was one of the pioneers of the cultural movement ‘tropicalismo'. This movement, with a strong character of social protest, combines elements of traditional Brazilian culture with modern art forms. Gilberto Gil's new sound clearly has its roots in Brazilian culture, yet it is always inspired by jazz.

programme.desc: The Danish Radio Big Band joins forces with American vocalist Curtis Stigers to celebrate Frank Sinatra's iconic concerts at The Sands Hotel in Las Vegas. Curtis Stigers and the big band present the most popular evergreens from the American songbook of the 1950s and 1960s, one of which is the classic that lend the concert its name: “Fly Me To The Moon”.

programme.title: Jazzmeia Horn
programme.desc: Vocalist Jazzmeia Horn's 2019 Malta Jazz Festival appearance was a celebration of jazz's future, infused with the soul of its past. Featuring Keith Brown (piano), Rashaan Carter (bass), Irwin Hall (flute and saxophone), and Anwar Marshall (drums), the young singer's performance was a reminder of jazz's enduring power to speak to the heart. Situated at the Valletta waterfront outside Our Lady of Liesse Church, Horn's concert was a truly spellbinding experience.

programme.title: Art Farmer, Jim Hall, Steve Swallow & Pete La Roca
programme.sub-title: The Art Farmer Quartet live In England
programme.desc: Art Farmer: Live in '64 highlights an amazing one-hour concert featuring the great flugelhornist in his prime. Farmer's band includes legendary guitarist Jim Hall (fresh from Sonny Rollins' band), drummer Pete LaRoca, and Steve Swallow on bass. The legendary ensemble plays both standards and originals with ease and finesse and highlights why Farmer was considered one of the most innovative horn players in all of jazz.

programme.title: Bill Evans
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: Dexter Gordon, George Gruntz, Guy Pedersen & Daniel Humair
programme.desc: Dexter Gordon: Live in '63 & '64 features three concerts filmed in Holland, Switzerland, and Belgium that highlight the bebop legend's classic style and silky tone. These shows feature legendary side musicians such as Art Taylor (drums) and Kenny Drew (piano), and jazz classics “Blues Walk”, “A Night In Tunisia”, “Body And Soul”, and others. One of the most influential saxophonists in jazz history, Dexter Gordon is captured in sharp form and style in this 70-minute tour de force.

programme.title: Chucho Valdis
programme.desc: Legendary Cuban pianist Chucho Valdés brought his band ‘Jazz Batá 2' to the Malta Jazz Festival on July 19, 2019. The air was thick with anticipation as Valdés took to the stage, revisiting the small-group concept of his mythical 1972 Cuban album ‘Jazz Batá'. The batá repertoire – the deep classical music of West Africa – permeates Valdés' piano solos throughout the concert. Valdés's band consists of Dreiser Durruthy (Batas and vocals), Yaroldy Abreu (percussions and vocals), Abraham Mansfarroll (percussion), Ramón Vazquez Martirena-Bajo (bass guitar). They delivered a performance that reverberated through the historic island.

programme.title: Mike Stern
programme.sub-title: Mike Stern & Didier Lockwood: Jazz à Vienne
programme.desc: Guitarist Mike Stern and violin player Didier Lockwood sharing a stage: that promises a good show! After playing for years with Blood, Sweat & Tears, Mike Stern landed a gig with drummer Billy Cobham and then broke through with Miles Davis' comeback band in the 1980s. Didier Lockwood played in jazz fusion band Magma during the 1970s and is known for his use of electric amplification and experimentation. Together they perform a unique duo concert at the beautiful antique theatre in Vienne, France.

programme.title: Milky Chance
programme.desc: The German duet is back and better than ever! Milky Chance is the success story of two school friends, Clemens Rehbein and Philipp Dausch. After a long break, 2017 marks the release of a second, long-waited, album "Blossom". And, for the public, finally the occasion to discover live these new compositions, mixing rock, folk and electro pop. With reggae vibrations that can rub shoulders with house elements, Milky Chance has one of the most singular sounds. With the presence of musicians on stage, and if we believe the listening of the new record, we can expect more electric concerts, more electronic and even more energetic than in the past!

programme.title: Progressive Rock
programme.desc: By the dawn of the seventies, progressive rock freed bands of the limitations of four-minute songs, allowing musicians to evolve a single track over a whole side of vinyl, draw on classical sources and create music in more complex, time signatures. Moog Synthesizers were portable and affordable, allowing bands to create orchestral effects. Such devices added a spectrum of new sounds and possibilities for musicians. This new world brought artists such as Rush, Yes & Atomic Rooster into the mainstream.

programme.title: Soft Rock
programme.desc: During the 1960s rock n roll splintered into a rainbow of genres – musicians were experimenting. Soft rock began as a blend of the progressive rock quest for musicianship and the songwriter's love of pop. It originated in the late 1960s in Southern California and the United Kingdom. The style relied on simple, melodic songs with big, lush productions. This new genre established bands such as Supertramp, ELO & Barclay James Harvest

programme.desc: Vivere Live in Tuscany is a concert by Italian classical singer Andrea Bocelli.

programme.title: Paul Simon
programme.desc: During the first leg of Paul Simon's triumphant, 2011 U.S. tour, he thrilled hometown fans with a special club performance at New York City's historic Webster Hall. The show presents this iconic artist working at the peak of his artistic and creative powers in an unusually intimate setting. The 20-song, 90-minute set list was drawn from his legendary career and includes several songs that haven't been performed live in many years. "Kodachrome," "Mother and Child Reunion," "Gone At Last" and "The Obvious Child" are just some of the highlights as well as songs from Simon's most recent album, 2011's So Beautiful or So What (Hear Music/Concord Music Group) including "Dazzling Blue," "Rewrite," "The Afterlife" and the album's propulsive title track.

programme.title: Adrien Perruchon, Symfonieorkest Vlaanderen & Josef Špaček
programme.sub-title: Works by Ravel, Lalo, Ginastera a. o.
programme.desc: French conductor Adrien Perruchon and the Flanders Symphony Orchestra take us on a musical journey to Argentine, Spain, and Mexico, in this March 1, 2017 concert performance at Concertgebouw Brugge in Belgium. The program opens with Édouard Lalo's Spanish Symphony for violin and orchestra, Op. 21, featuring Czech violinist Josef Špaček as the soloist. This is followed by Mathias Coppens' Music for Orchestra, Op. 12. The program continues with Alberto Ginastera's Dances from Estancia, Op. 8a, and Aaron Copland's El Salón México. Also on the program is Maurice Ravel's famous Boléro. The program comes to a close with Arturo Márquez's Danzón No. 2.

programme.title: Evgeny Kissin, Nikolai Demidenko, Warsaw Philharmonic Orchestra & Antoni Wit
programme.desc: Antoni Wit conducts the Warsaw Philharmonic Orchestra in performances of Chopin's Piano Concertos No. 1, Op. 11 and No. 2, Op. 21. Soloists are Nikolai Demidenko and Evgeny Kissin. After performing the first concerto, Demidenko encores with Chopin's Mazurka Op. 17/4. Kissin closes the concert with Chopin's Etude Op. 10/12 and the Waltz in E minor, Op. post. This concert was part of the celebration of Chopin's 200th anniversary in 2010. Chopin composed the second concerto one year before the Concerto No. 1 and completed both works at the age of 20, before leaving his home country Poland and moving to Paris.

programme.title: Les Dissonances & David Grimal
programme.sub-title: Brahms - Symphony No. 1 in C minor, Op. 68
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances present Johannes Brahms's Symphony No. 1 in C minor, Op. 68. Brahms realized he was expected to compose a symphony that would match the musical standards established by Ludwig van Beethoven. After working on it for at least fourteen years, he completed his Symphony No. 1 in 1876. Brahms's symphony was hailed as ‘Beethoven's Tenth': a worthy successor to Beethoven's Symphony No. 9. Brahms's work contains several references to Beethoven. For instance, the main theme of the fourth movement – first appearing in the strings – resembles the ‘Ode to Joy' in the finale of Beethoven's Symphony No. 9. This performance was recorded at Philharmonie de Paris, France, in 2014.

programme.title: Mikhail Pletnev, Russian National Orchestra & Lucas Debargue
programme.sub-title: Pletnev conducts Bizet & Ravel's Concerto No. 1
programme.desc: Mikhail Pletnev leads the Russian National Orchestra (RNO) in a performance of Maurice Ravel's Piano Concerto No. 1 with Lucas Debargue as the soloist. The concert opens with a selection of music by Georges Bizet based on Alphonse Daudet's play 'L'Arlésienne'. The music is compiled by Mikhail Pletnev. The first movement of Ravel's Piano Concerto No. 1 contains five distinctive themes, of which three are reminiscent of jazz. Debargue's performance of Ravel's concerto is followed by Gabriel Fauré's Barcarolle No. 4. The performance was recorded at Tchaikovsky Concert Hall in Moscow as part of the Ninth RNO Grand Festival.

programme.title: Philippe Jordan, Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris, Choeur de l'Opéra national de Paris & Ricarda Merbeth
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125
programme.desc: Swiss conductor Philippe Jordan and the Orchestre de l'Opéra national de Paris recorded all of Ludwig van Beethoven's symphonies in 2014-2015. In this program, maestro Jordan presents Beethoven's final symphony: Symphony No. 9 in D minor, Op. 125. He conducts the Orchestre and Choeurs de l'Opéra national de Paris and four vocal soloists Ricarda Merbeth (soprano), Daniela Sindram (mezzosoprano), Robert Dean Smith (tenor), and Günther Groissböck (bass). Beethoven composed his last Symphony when his hearing had all but gone, between 1822 and 1824. Symphony No. 9 is the longest and most ambitious of Beethoven's symphonies. Most striking is the piece's finale movement, which includes a choir and four vocal soloists singing a setting of Friedrich Schiller's poem ‘An die Freude' (Ode to Joy). This performance was recorded at Opéra Bastille in Paris, France, in 2015.

"Dolphin Voyage Relaxation" is 1-hour long and features some spectacular underwater cinematography by Peter Schneider and a synergistic blend of audio including underwater nature sounds, calming ambient music by The Cynic Project, and a subtle background layer of harmonically tuned binaural relaxation sounds by Schmidt. The result is an immersive, awe-inspiring adventure with gracefully transitions, leaving the viewer with a powerful dose of calm and healing energy direct from Nature.
